<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="370" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1512,2043]" box="[199,945,1584,1611]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1584,1611]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Description.</emphasis>
Species identification is based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Linnavuori, R." box="[732,942,1585,1611]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369" pagination="1 - 17" refId="ref7467" refString="Linnavuori, R. (1978) Studies on the family Cicadellidae (Homoptera, Auchenorrhyncha). 1. A revision of the Macropsinae of the Ethiopian Region. Acta Entomologica Fennica, 33, 1 - 17." type="journal article" year="1978">Linnavuori (1978)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1512,2043]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Two studied males differ from each other in coloration, although similar in shape of genitalia and 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1319,1335,1620,1634]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">nd</superScript>
abdominal apodemes. Dark coloured male greyish yellow with strongly developed dark pattern (
<figureCitation box="[1163,1301,1657,1684]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–22" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[161,1422,173,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1433,166,1785]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–22. 1–3—Macropsis simplex Jacobi, female (1—lateral view; 2—dorsal view; 3—face); 4–5—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n., male (4—lateral view; 5—dorsal view); 6–12—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori), female (6–8—holotype, photos by Alyssa Seemann; 9–12—females from Ambo, Ethiopia; 6, 9—face and pronotum; 7, 10–11—lateral view; 8, 12—dorsal view); 13–15—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n., female (13—lateral view; 14—dorsal view; 15—face); 16–22—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori (16, 19—male, lateral view; 17, 21—same, face; 18, 20—same, dorsal view; 22—female, lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772389/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Figs. 16–18</figureCitation>
). Head pale yellow with two round black spots on crown, two black transverse stripes, both interrupted in middle, and blurry brown spots on frons. Pronotum greyish yellow with two large dark spots on fore margin behind eyes, mesonotum brown with yellow lateral margins and back third and with black tip. Proepimeron with black spot. Forewing semitransparent with brown speckles; tip of clavus, ends of claval veins, and some veins in apical half of wing (mostly, transverse ones) darkened.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1512,2043]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Light coloured male entirely yellowish green with two small black spots on crown, almost invisible black spot on proepimeron and few speckles on forewing (
<figureCitation box="[686,823,1909,1935]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–22" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[161,1422,173,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1433,166,1785]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–22. 1–3—Macropsis simplex Jacobi, female (1—lateral view; 2—dorsal view; 3—face); 4–5—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n., male (4—lateral view; 5—dorsal view); 6–12—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori), female (6–8—holotype, photos by Alyssa Seemann; 9–12—females from Ambo, Ethiopia; 6, 9—face and pronotum; 7, 10–11—lateral view; 8, 12—dorsal view); 13–15—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n., female (13—lateral view; 14—dorsal view; 15—face); 16–22—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori (16, 19—male, lateral view; 17, 21—same, face; 18, 20—same, dorsal view; 22—female, lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772389/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Figs. 19–21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1512,2043]" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">
Female entirely yellowish green with more or less developed speckled pattern on forewing with the exception of clavus and with whitish median stripe on mesonotum; in the female with most strongly developed pattern on forewing the very tip of mesonotum black (
<figureCitation box="[638,722,2017,2043]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–22" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[161,1422,173,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1433,166,1785]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–22. 1–3—Macropsis simplex Jacobi, female (1—lateral view; 2—dorsal view; 3—face); 4–5—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n., male (4—lateral view; 5—dorsal view); 6–12—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori), female (6–8—holotype, photos by Alyssa Seemann; 9–12—females from Ambo, Ethiopia; 6, 9—face and pronotum; 7, 10–11—lateral view; 8, 12—dorsal view); 13–15—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n., female (13—lateral view; 14—dorsal view; 15—face); 16–22—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori (16, 19—male, lateral view; 17, 21—same, face; 18, 20—same, dorsal view; 22—female, lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772389/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="369">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,683]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">
Apex of crown and anterior margin of pronotum rounded (
<figureCitation box="[877,1019,153,179]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–22" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1804,1829]" captionTargetBox="[161,1422,173,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1433,166,1785]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–22. 1–3—Macropsis simplex Jacobi, female (1—lateral view; 2—dorsal view; 3—face); 4–5—M. tincta Tisheсhkin sp. n., male (4—lateral view; 5—dorsal view); 6–12—M. tuberculata (Linnavuori), female (6–8—holotype, photos by Alyssa Seemann; 9–12—females from Ambo, Ethiopia; 6, 9—face and pronotum; 7, 10–11—lateral view; 8, 12—dorsal view); 13–15—M. viridofulgida Tisheсhkin sp. n., female (13—lateral view; 14—dorsal view; 15—face); 16–22—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori (16, 19—male, lateral view; 17, 21—same, face; 18, 20—same, dorsal view; 22—female, lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772389/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figs. 18, 20</figureCitation>
). Median keel weakly developed, in males hardly distinguishable only on mesonotum, in females distinct on mesonotum and in upper half of face.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,153,683]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">
Abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[493,509,224,238]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">nd</superScript>
tergite in male with rather short angular lobes separated by wide round notch (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 82–117" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[246,1350,176,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[236,1352,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 82–117. 82–94—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori; 95–108—M. nikippa Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 109–117—M. antibia Tisheсhkin sp. n. 82–83, 95–96—male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 84–85, 97–98―the 2nd sternite; 86–87, 99–100, 110—penis, lateral view; 88–89, 101–102, 113—style; 90—pygofer processes, back view; 91–92, 103–104, 111—pygofer process, lateral view; 105, 112—pygofer process, dorsolateral view; 93, 106–107, 114–115—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 94, 108, 116–117—female 7th sternite; 109—male 2nd abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772395/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figs. 82–83</figureCitation>
); sternal apodemes with narrow tips sometimes slightly bent inwards, separated by wide more or less round notch (
<figureCitation box="[230,369,296,323]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–117" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[246,1350,176,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[236,1352,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 82–117. 82–94—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori; 95–108—M. nikippa Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 109–117—M. antibia Tisheсhkin sp. n. 82–83, 95–96—male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 84–85, 97–98―the 2nd sternite; 86–87, 99–100, 110—penis, lateral view; 88–89, 101–102, 113—style; 90—pygofer processes, back view; 91–92, 103–104, 111—pygofer process, lateral view; 105, 112—pygofer process, dorsolateral view; 93, 106–107, 114–115—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 94, 108, 116–117—female 7th sternite; 109—male 2nd abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772395/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figs. 84–85</figureCitation>
). Penis in side view slender, evenly tapering apically (
<figureCitation box="[983,1122,297,324]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–117" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[246,1350,176,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[236,1352,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 82–117. 82–94—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori; 95–108—M. nikippa Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 109–117—M. antibia Tisheсhkin sp. n. 82–83, 95–96—male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 84–85, 97–98―the 2nd sternite; 86–87, 99–100, 110—penis, lateral view; 88–89, 101–102, 113—style; 90—pygofer processes, back view; 91–92, 103–104, 111—pygofer process, lateral view; 105, 112—pygofer process, dorsolateral view; 93, 106–107, 114–115—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 94, 108, 116–117—female 7th sternite; 109—male 2nd abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772395/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figs. 86–87</figureCitation>
). Style tip pointed or somewhat expanded (
<figureCitation box="[333,470,333,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–117" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[246,1350,176,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[236,1352,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 82–117. 82–94—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori; 95–108—M. nikippa Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 109–117—M. antibia Tisheсhkin sp. n. 82–83, 95–96—male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 84–85, 97–98―the 2nd sternite; 86–87, 99–100, 110—penis, lateral view; 88–89, 101–102, 113—style; 90—pygofer processes, back view; 91–92, 103–104, 111—pygofer process, lateral view; 105, 112—pygofer process, dorsolateral view; 93, 106–107, 114–115—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 94, 108, 116–117—female 7th sternite; 109—male 2nd abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772395/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figs. 88–89</figureCitation>
). Pygofer lobes in back parts thin, semi-transparent in macerated preparations, but with strongly sclerotized ribs along back margins (
<figureCitation box="[667,752,369,395]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–117" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1860,1885]" captionTargetBox="[246,1350,176,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[236,1352,166,1840]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 82–117. 82–94—Macropsis hippodameia Linnavuori; 95–108—M. nikippa Tisheсhkin sp. n.; 109–117—M. antibia Tisheсhkin sp. n. 82–83, 95–96—male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 84–85, 97–98―the 2nd sternite; 86–87, 99–100, 110—penis, lateral view; 88–89, 101–102, 113—style; 90—pygofer processes, back view; 91–92, 103–104, 111—pygofer process, lateral view; 105, 112—pygofer process, dorsolateral view; 93, 106–107, 114–115—2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 94, 108, 116–117—female 7th sternite; 109—male 2nd abdominal apodemes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772395/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Fig. 90</figureCitation>
). Pygofer processes in back view parallel, somewhat sinuate (
